{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504982","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504982"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:24:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:24:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2392"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2392","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2392"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.17,0.05,0.33,0.39]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2392"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112383"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2392","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2392"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2392"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94431"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"181"},{"type":"tags","id":"1172"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1548"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1561"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15266"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15503"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18358"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46022"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112383","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112383"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 67-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a seven-day history of fatigue, nausea and lightheadedness. He has a medical history of Child-Pugh class C cirrhosis secondary to alcohol use disorder and metabolic dysfunction-associated steatotic liver disease. His medications include furosemide, spironolactone and an angiotensin receptor blocker for hypertension.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell with pulse rate 92/min, blood pressure 105/65 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 97% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. His abdomen is soft and non-tender with moderate ascites and bilateral pitting oedema to the mid-shins.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Esodium 121 mmol/L (136-145)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Epotassium 5.6 mmol/L (3.5-5.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eurea 12.5 mmol/L (2.5-7.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ecreatinine 145 \u03bcmol/L (60-110)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eprothrombin time 18 seconds (11-15)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ealbumin 28 g/L (35-50)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ebilirubin 45 \u03bcmol/L (3-20)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Increase dose of furosemide and spironolactone","Increase dose of furosemide only","Arrange outpatient paracentesis","Intravenous albumin infusion","Intravenous hypertonic saline"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient with decompensated cirrhosis presents with hyponatraemia (121 mmol/L), which is a common complication of advanced liver disease and carries a poor prognosis. The pathophysiology involves splanchnic vasodilation leading to reduced effective arterial volume, which triggers compensatory activation of the renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system and antidiuretic hormone release, resulting in impaired free water excretion and dilutional hyponatraemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous albumin infusion\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate initial management. Albumin improves effective arterial volume and renal perfusion, thereby enhancing free water clearance and gradually correcting hyponatraemia. A typical regimen involves 500 mL of 20% albumin infused over 12 hours. This approach is safer than rapid sodium correction and addresses the underlying pathophysiology. While this patient\u0027s sodium level of 121 mmol/L is not below the threshold for severe hyponatraemia requiring hypertonic saline, albumin remains the preferred initial treatment in the absence of cerebral symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncrease dose of furosemide and spironolactone\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003EIncrease dose of furosemide only\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate and potentially dangerous. Diuretics can worsen hyponatraemia by promoting further sodium loss and should be withheld in this setting. The patient\u0027s elevated potassium also contraindicates increasing spironolactone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArrange outpatient paracentesis\u003C/strong\u003E is inappropriate given the severity of the hyponatraemia requiring urgent inpatient management. While paracentesis may be needed for symptomatic ascites, it does not address the immediate electrolyte disturbance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous hypertonic saline\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated in this case as there is no severe hyponatraemia (sodium \u0026lt;120 mmol/L or with cerebral symptoms). Rapid sodium correction with intravenous hypertonic saline may precipitate osmotic demyelination syndrome (previously called central pontine myelinolysis). The goal is gradual correction of 4-6 mmol/L per 24 hours, not exceeding nine mmol/L in the first day.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAdditional management should include withholding the angiotensin receptor blocker and diuretics, implementing fluid restriction to 1-1.5 L daily, and monitoring sodium levels closely to ensure appropriate correction rate.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Intravenous albumin infusion can provide effective short-term management of cirrhosis-related hyponatraemia by improving renal perfusion and free water clearance.","Diuretics and angiotensin receptor blockers should be withheld in cirrhotic patients with significant hyponatraemia as they can worsen sodium levels.","Hyponatraemia in cirrhosis results from splanchnic vasodilation and compensatory neurohormonal activation leading to impaired free water excretion."],"references":["Savio J, Thuluvath P. Hyponatremia in cirrhosis: Pathophysiology and management. World J Gastroenterol. 2015 Mar;21(11):3197-205","Alukal, J. J., John, S., \u0026 Thuluvath, P. J. (2020). Hyponatremia in Cirrhosis: An Update. The American journal of gastroenterology, 115(11), 1775\u20131785. Available at: https://journals.lww.com/ajg/abstract/2020/11000/hyponatremia_in_cirrhosis__an_update.11.aspx","Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Electrolyte abnormalities. In: eTG complete [Internet]. Melbourne (Australia): Therapeutic Guidelines; Published Mar 2014, amended Mar 2021 [cited 2025 Aug 30]. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94431"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2392"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94431","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94431"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-31T08:40:39+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-31T08:41:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2392"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112383"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"